        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Spectral resolution: 
Pineda et al. (2011) observed CO linewidths &lt;~ 1  kms in L1451-mm. The FHSC radiative transfer modelling of CS by Tomisaka &amp; Tomida (2011) predicts CS linewidths of around 2 kms, which contain a plethora of fine structure (at the level of ~ 0.1 kms), from which the infall and outflow properties of gas near the core (and accretion disk) may be derived. To adequately resolve these complex line profiles, we request 61 kHz spectral resolution (approx. 0.08 km/s). 244 kHz resolution (approx. 0.3 km/s) will be sufficient for CH3OH, H2CO and HC3N.


Sensitivity and angular resolution:
The predicted small-scale FHSC outflow extends 1-2'' from the source. This will be resolved (edge-on) with an angular resolution of 0.5'', attainable in Band 6 using ALMA configuration C34-4.

Peak brightness temperatures of T_B ~ 30-50 K are typical for the 12CO outflows observed from low-mass protostars (Arce et al. 2006; Yeh et al. 2008; Chen et al. 2010; Pineda et al. 2011), so the outflow from Cha-MMS1 should be detected after only a few minutes of integration. However, higher sensitivity ( &lt;~ 1 K) will be needed to detect the weaker line wings which are required to fully characterise the outflow. The proposed 13CO and CS lines are expected to be a factor of 5-10 weaker than CO (with T_B ~ 5 K), so we request an RMS brightness temperature sensitivity of 0.5 K per resolution element to obtain approx. 10-sigma detections, necessary for analysing their profiles.

Typical densities inside hot corinos are ~ 10^8-10^9 cm^-3 (Jorgensen et al. 2002), and Maret et al. derived hot corino H2CO and CH3OH fractional abundances of ~ 10^-7. Thus, averaged over a 10 AU hot core, the column densities of these molecules are predicted to be ~ 5x10^15 cm^-2. Using the RADEX non-LTE radiative transfer code (van der Tak et al. 2007), we predict that the resulting H2CO J_{K_aK_c}=3_{13}-2_{11} and 3_{03}-2_{02} lines (at 225.7 and 218.2 GHz, respectively), will be optically thick (assuming a linewidth of 1 kms), and reach brightness temperatures approaching 100 K. Accounting for the ALMA beam dilution factor, the predicted H2CO line brightness temperatures are ~ 2 K for the putative hot core of Cha-MMS1. An RMS sensitivity of 0.3 K per resolution element will be sufficient to detect these lines.

Two LO settings are required: one for 12CO, CS, H2CO and CH3OH and one for 13CO, HC3N and the additional H2CO and CH3OH lines.  According to the ALMA Sensitivity Calculator, using the above parameters with default water vapour column and dual polarization, an on-source integration time of about 1 hr per setting is required. Including overheads, the total observing time request is 5.4 hr.


UV Coverage / Imaging requirements: 
Our science goals do not require the detailed structure of the outflow or hot core to be mapped, and sufficient uv-coverage to distinguish the outflow lobes will be obtained with a snapshot observation. Typical CO outflows from nearby Class 0 protostars are observed to extend &gt; ~ 30'' from the core (eg. Arce et al. 2006; Yeh et al. 2008; Chen et al. 2010). However, the slower outflow from the FHSC candidate L1451-mm extends much less far (approx. 3'', in line with numerical simulations; Pineda et al. 2011) and should easily fit within the 22'' Band 6 field-of-view. Similarly, although CO outflows show structure over a broad range of angular scales, a 10'' maximum recoverable scale is expected to be sufficient to detect the majority of flux from the outflow.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
